---
id: org.dxos.plugin.support
name: SupportPlugin
version: 0.1.0
---

Composer's user-facing assistance plugin. Covers two paths:

1. **Conversational support** — users open a `Ticket` from the navtree and the AI
   assistant collaborates on diagnosing the issue, searching documentation, and
   recording the resolution. Tickets are ECHO objects so a conversation is
   local-first, replicable to other devices, and reviewable by a human
   supporter later.
2. **One-shot feedback** — users send anonymous feedback (with optional debug
   logs) to the observability backend via the deck `--help` companion. This
   replaces the same surface previously owned by plugin-observability and
   keeps the telemetry plugin focused on instrumentation only.
3. **GitHub issue submission** — same form, optional third action: file a
   structured bug/feature request against the upstream repo. When the user
   has authenticated the GitHub integration (via plugin-integration) the
   issue is filed as them via the GitHub API; otherwise we open a prefilled
   `issues/new` URL in a new tab so the user can finish the submission in
   their own browser session.

A future iteration will absorb plugin-help (welcome tour, contextual hints,
keyboard shortcuts) so all user education lives here.

Initial scope is a thin skeleton: a `Ticket` schema, four ticket operations
wired to a skill, a `FeedbackForm` + `captureUserFeedback` operation, and
two surfaces (`Ticket` article + `--help` companion). Documentation search and
issue filing are stubbed — the skill exists so the assistant can be
exercised end-to-end while the integrations land in later phases.

## Extensions

The following extension dialects are used in this document.

| Term        | URI                            |
|-------------|--------------------------------|
| `type`      | `org.dxos.mdl.type@1.0`       |
| `feat`      | `org.dxos.mdl.feat@1.0`       |
| `test`      | `org.dxos.mdl.test@1.0`       |
| `component` | `org.dxos.mdl.component@1.0`  |
| `op`        | `org.dxos.mdl.op@1.0`         |

## Types

```mdl
type TicketStatus
  literals: open | in_progress | resolved
```

```mdl
type Ticket
  desc: >
    A user-reported support ticket. Conversation history is kept by the
    AI assistant in a separate ECHO conversation; the Ticket itself
    carries the summary and the resolution status.
  fields:
    title: string
    body?: string                # Initial description of the problem.
    status: TicketStatus
    resolution?: string          # Resolution notes written when status -> resolved.
    tags: string[]               # Free-form tags (e.g. echo, ui, performance).
```

```mdl
type IssueType
  literals: bug | feature
```

```mdl
type Severity
  # Literal strings double as GitHub label names so a triager can read
  # the priority at a glance from the labels strip on the filed issue.
  literals: "High priority" | "Medium priority" | "Low priority"
```

```mdl
type SupportRequest
  desc: >
    Form payload submitted from the help companion. Drives all three
    submission paths: PostHog (one-shot feedback), Discord (help thread),
    and GitHub issue. The hidden field `version` is populated by the
    FeedbackPanel from the runtime config; the user never edits it but
    it is forwarded to the backend so support triage can identify the
    build the report came from.
  fields:
    type: IssueType              # bug | feature
    severity: Severity           # "High priority" | "Medium priority" | "Low priority"
    title: string                # Short summary (becomes GH issue title).
    body: string                 # Longer description (becomes GH issue body).
    area?: string                # Plugin id (e.g. org.dxos.plugin.echo). Optional.
    includeLogs?: boolean        # Forward debug logs with the submission.
    version?: string             # Hidden: app build version. Auto-populated.
```

## Components

```mdl
component SupportArticle
  desc: >
    Article surface bound to a Ticket. Displays title, body, status and
    resolution. The assistant chat lives in the standard chat companion
    surface; this article is the persistent record.
  props:
    ticket: Ticket
  slots:
    toolbar?: ReactNode
  actions:
    setTitle(value: string)
    setBody(value: string)
    setResolution(value: string)
    setStatus(status: TicketStatus)
  layout: |
    ┌─────────────────────────────────┐
    │ [toolbar slot] status: open     │
    ├─────────────────────────────────┤
    │ Title  [_______________________]│
    │ Body   [_______________________]│
    │        [_______________________]│
    ├─────────────────────────────────┤
    │ Resolution                      │
    │        [_______________________]│
    ├─────────────────────────────────┤
    │ [Mark in progress] [Resolve]    │
    └─────────────────────────────────┘
```

## Operations

```mdl
op createTicket
  desc: Creates a new Ticket in the active space.
  input:
    title: string
    body?: string
  output: Ticket
  effects: [echo:write]
```

```mdl
op markInProgress
  desc: Marks a Ticket as in progress (active investigation).
  input:
    ticket: Ticket
  output: Ticket
  effects: [echo:write]
```

```mdl
op resolveTicket
  desc: Marks a Ticket as resolved with optional resolution notes.
  input:
    ticket: Ticket
    resolution?: string
  output: Ticket
  effects: [echo:write]
```

```mdl
op searchDocs
  desc: >
    Searches Composer / DXOS documentation for the given query and returns
    a list of excerpts. Stub implementation in the initial phase; later
    backed by an embedded vector index or a remote search endpoint.
  input:
    query: string
    limit?: number
  output:
    results: { title: string, url: string, excerpt: string }[]
```

```mdl
op captureUserFeedback
  desc: >
    Sends a one-shot feedback message (with optional debug logs) to the
    observability backend. Backed by the Observability capability contributed
    by plugin-observability — plugin-support owns the UI and operation; the
    actual transport stays in the observability plugin.
  input:
    message: string
    includeLogs?: boolean
  output: void
```

GitHub issue submission is performed inline by the FeedbackPanel — it
queries the user's personal space for an `AccessToken` with source
`github.com`, POSTs to the GitHub API if found, and falls back to opening
a prefilled `issues/new` URL otherwise. No dedicated operation is exposed
in this phase; if AI / CLI invocation is needed later, add one wrapping
the same flow.

## Features

```mdl
feat F-1: Ticket Lifecycle

  req F-1.1: User can create a Ticket from the AI assistant or directly via the navtree.
  req F-1.2:
    when: a Ticket is created
    then: status === open; resolution unset.
  req F-1.3:
    when: assistant or user calls markInProgress
    then: status === in_progress.
  req F-1.4:
    when: assistant or user calls resolveTicket
    then: status === resolved; resolution recorded (if provided).
  req F-1.5: Ticket title and body are editable in SupportArticle.
  req F-1.6:
    when: user clicks Reopen on a resolved Ticket in SupportArticle
    then: status === open (UI-driven; no dedicated op).
```

```mdl
feat F-2: AI Support Assistant

  req F-2.1: A skill is registered with key org.dxos.skill.support.
  req F-2.2: Skill tools include createTicket, markInProgress, resolveTicket, searchDocs.
  req F-2.3:
    when: a Ticket is the active object
    then: the support skill is bound to the chat companion surface.
  req F-2.4: The assistant is instructed to gather details, search docs, and only resolve when the user confirms.
```

```mdl
feat F-3: Documentation Search

  req F-3.1: searchDocs operation is defined with a query input.
  req F-3.2:
    when: assistant calls searchDocs
    then: zero or more {title,url,excerpt} results are returned.
  req F-3.3: Initial implementation returns a small in-memory set; replaceable without changing the schema.
```

```mdl
feat F-4: One-shot Feedback

  req F-4.1: plugin-support contributes the deck `--help` companion surface; it renders a FeedbackForm.
  req F-4.2:
    when: user submits the FeedbackForm
    then: captureUserFeedback runs and forwards to the Observability capability.
  req F-4.3:
    when: feedback succeeds
    then: a confirmation toast is shown and the companion collapses.
  req F-4.4: When the LogDownloader capability is contributed, a "Download logs" action is offered alongside the form.
  req F-4.5:
    when: the Observability capability reports feedback is unavailable
    then: the submit button is disabled.
```

```mdl
feat F-5: GitHub Issue Submission

  req F-5.1: FeedbackForm exposes type (bug/feature), severity, title, body, and area (optional plugin) alongside the existing submit + Discord actions.
  req F-5.2: The form auto-populates and submits a hidden `version` field (app build) without rendering it as an input.
  req F-5.3: The area select is populated from the runtime plugin list (plugin id + name); empty selection is allowed.
  req F-5.4:
    when: user clicks "Create GitHub issue"
    then: submitGitHubIssue is invoked with the form values.
  req F-5.5:
    when: an AccessToken with source `github.com` is present in the active space
    then: the issue is POSTed to the GitHub API; the response URL is opened in a new tab and a success toast is shown.
  req F-5.6:
    when: no GitHub AccessToken is present
    then: a prefilled `issues/new` URL is opened in a new tab; the user finishes the submission manually.
  req F-5.7: type maps to GitHub's Issue Type field via `?type=Bug` / `?type=Feature`; severity is emitted as a label whose name matches the literal (e.g. `High priority`); area, when set, adds an `area/<plugin-id>` label. A `Composer` source-anchor label is always included.
```

## Acceptance

```mdl
test T-1: Create a ticket
  given: user is in a space
  when: createTicket invoked with title "Echo sync hung"
  then:
    - Ticket created in space
    - status === open
    - title === "Echo sync hung"
```

```mdl
test T-2: Resolve a ticket
  given: an open Ticket
  when: resolveTicket invoked with resolution "Restarted client"
  then:
    - status === resolved
    - resolution === "Restarted client"
```

```mdl
test T-3: SupportArticle renders ticket
  given: a Ticket with title and body
  when: SupportArticle is rendered
  then:
    - title visible and editable
    - body visible and editable
    - status indicator reflects ticket.status
```

```mdl
test T-4: Resolve button updates status
  given: SupportArticle is shown for an open Ticket
  when: user clicks the Resolve button
  then:
    - Ticket.status === resolved
```

```mdl
test T-5: Mark in progress
  given: an open Ticket
  when: markInProgress invoked (via assistant or UI button)
  then:
    - Ticket.status === in_progress
```

```mdl
test T-6: Reopen a resolved ticket
  given: a resolved Ticket shown in SupportArticle
  when: user clicks the Reopen button
  then:
    - Ticket.status === open
```
